INDICATIONS: This patient is a 79-year-old male with an asymptomatic 7-cm abdominal aortic aneurysm noted incidentally on a CT scan for a small bowel obstruction. He presents for aortogram with evaluation for possible endograft repair.
MEDICATIONS AND CONTRAST: The patient received no IV sedation during the procedure, however was continuously hemodynamically monitored throughout the case. 8 cc of 1% lidocaine were used as local anesthesia and a total of 240 cc of Optiray 60% contrast was used throughout the case.
TECHNIQUE: After consent was obtained, patient was placed in the supine position on the fluoroscopy table and the right groin was shaved, prepped, and draped in the usual sterile manner. Common femoral artery was identified with the aid of fluoroscopic guidance using bony landmarks. 8 cc of 1% lidocaine local anesthesia were infiltrated at the site of the right common femoral artery and a 19-gauge single wall puncture needle was introduced into the right common femoral artery after a small skin [**Doctor Last Name **] was made with an #11 blade and 0.035" Bentson guidewire was then advanced through the needle and into the lower abdominal aorta. A 5-French sheath was then placed over the wire and its side arm was flushed throughout the case with heparinized saline. Over the wire, a 5-French marked Omniflush catheter was inserted to the level of L1 and abdominal aortogram was performed including AP and lateral views. The catheter tip was then withdrawn to the level of the lower abdominal aorta and right and left anterior oblique views of the pelvic arteriogram were performed. Subsequently, a bilateral femoral arteriogram was performed. The catheter was removed. The sheath was removed and adequate hemostasis was achieved with manual pressure at the puncture site. The patient tolerated the procedure well. No immediate complications were noted.
FINDINGS: The celiac trunk is patent, although mild stenosis of the proximal celiac trunk is noted on the lateral view of the aorta. Patent single bilateral renal arteries are noted with the left renal artery being lower than the right. Distance from the lower renal artery to the aortic bifurcation is 13 cm. The distance from the aortic bifurcation to the right iliac bifurcation is 8 cm. There is about a 40 degree lateral angulation of the infrarenal aorta. In the lateral view, there is mild posterior angulation of the infrarenal aorta. The right iliac system is more tortuous than the left. Bilateral common internal and external iliac arteries are patent. The femoral arteries are also widely patent, as are the superficial femoral and profunda femoris arteries. Bilateral superficial femoral arteries have diffuse mild disease.
